---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  { question: "What is GitOps and how is it different from traditional CI/CD?", answer: "GitOps is a deployment model where the Git repository is the single source of truth for the desired state of your infrastructure and applications. Traditional CI/CD pushes changes: a pipeline runs tests, builds an image, and uses kubectl apply or helm upgrade to push the change to the cluster. GitOps pulls changes: an agent (Flux or ArgoCD) runs inside the cluster, watches the Git repo, and continuously reconciles — pulling in changes when the desired state in Git differs from the actual cluster state. Benefits: full audit trail via Git history, rollback via git revert, cluster state is always reproducible from the repo, and no CI system needs cluster credentials." },
  { question: "Does ArgoCD or Flux have better multi-tenancy support?", answer: "Both support multi-tenancy but differently. ArgoCD uses Projects to isolate teams — a Project defines which repos, clusters, and namespaces a team can deploy to, with RBAC rules. It has a full UI where teams can manage their applications. Flux uses a multi-tenant model via namespaced Flux resources — each tenant has their own Kustomization and HelmRelease objects scoped to their namespace, and you use Kubernetes RBAC to prevent cross-namespace access. Flux also supports 'sharding' where multiple Flux instances handle different tenants. ArgoCD's UI makes multi-tenancy operationally easier for teams without kubectl access; Flux's model is more Kubernetes-native and requires less centralized infrastructure." },
  { question: "How does secret management work with GitOps?", answer: "You can't store plain secrets in Git. The main patterns: (1) Sealed Secrets — encrypt secrets with a controller's public key; the encrypted SealedSecret is safe to commit and only decryptable by the in-cluster controller. (2) External Secrets Operator (ESO) — sync secrets from Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, or GCP Secret Manager into Kubernetes Secrets; the ESO manifest (safe to commit) references external secret sources. (3) SOPS — encrypt secrets at the file level using age or GPG; Flux has native SOPS decryption support. (4) Vault Agent Injector — inject secrets directly into pods at runtime. Most teams with GitOps use ESO or SOPS. ArgoCD also supports Vault plugin and ESO well." },
  { question: "Can I use Flux and ArgoCD on the same cluster?", answer: "Yes, but it's not recommended except for migration periods. Both tools watch and reconcile cluster state — having two controllers reconciling the same resources creates conflicts. If you're migrating from one to the other, run them side by side with non-overlapping namespace scopes: have ArgoCD manage some namespaces and Flux manage others. Complete the migration, validate, then remove the old tool. Some organizations use ArgoCD for application deployments and Flux for platform/infrastructure components (cert-manager, ingress, monitoring) — this can work if you're careful about non-overlapping resource ownership." },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Flux vs ArgoCD — GitOps Feature Matrix: Sync, Rollback, Multi-tenancy, Secrets"
  description="Compare Flux and ArgoCD for GitOps: sync mechanisms, rollback, multi-tenancy, UI, secrets management, and decision guide. Includes HelmRelease and Application examples."
  tool="Flux vs ArgoCD, GitOps, Flux HelmRelease, ArgoCD Application, Kubernetes GitOps, continuous delivery, GitOps secrets"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "Flux vs ArgoCD GitOps Comparison",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/gitops-flux-vs-argocd",
    "description": "Detailed Flux vs ArgoCD comparison with feature matrix, HelmRelease and Application examples, and decision guide.",
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Flux vs ArgoCD — GitOps Comparison</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
    Choose between <strong>Flux</strong> and <strong>ArgoCD</strong> for GitOps deployments. Compare sync mechanisms, rollback, multi-tenancy, UI capabilities, and secrets integration with practical examples.
  </p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Feature comparison table</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Flux HelmRelease example</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> ArgoCD Application example</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Decision guide</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Feature Matrix</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Feature</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Flux v2</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 font-semibold">ArgoCD</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-text-muted">
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Architecture</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Multi-controller (source/kustomize/helm)</td><td class="py-2">Single server + repo server</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="py-2 pr-4">UI</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Weave GitOps (separate), limited built-in</td><td class="py-2">✓ Rich built-in web UI</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Sync interval</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Configurable per resource</td><td class="py-2">Configurable per app (default 3m)</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Rollback</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Git revert (manual) or suspend + prev version</td><td class="py-2">✓ One-click rollback to any history</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Multi-tenancy</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">K8s RBAC + namespace scoping</td><td class="py-2">Projects + RBAC (UI-managed)</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Secrets</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">SOPS native support</td><td class="py-2">Plugins (argocd-vault-plugin, ESO)</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Multi-cluster</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">✓ Fleet of clusters</td><td class="py-2">✓ ApplicationSets</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Helm support</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">HelmRelease CRD</td><td class="py-2">Native Helm (or raw manifest)</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Progressive delivery</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Flagger integration</td><td class="py-2">Argo Rollouts (separate install)</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="py-2 pr-4">CNCF status</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Graduated</td><td class="py-2">Graduated</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">GitLab/GitHub webhooks</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">✓ Receiver webhook</td><td class="py-2">✓ Native webhook</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Flux — Bootstrap and HelmRelease Example</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4"># Bootstrap Flux onto your cluster (points to your Git repo)
flux bootstrap github \
  --owner=my-org \
  --repository=fleet-infra \
  --branch=main \
  --path=clusters/production \
  --personal

# HelmRelease resource — clusters/production/apps/nginx/helmrelease.yaml
apiVersion: helm.toolkit.fluxcd.io/v2beta2
kind: HelmRelease
metadata:
  name: nginx-ingress
  namespace: ingress-nginx
spec:
  interval: 10m
  chart:
    spec:
      chart: ingress-nginx
      version: "4.x"
      sourceRef:
        kind: HelmRepository
        name: ingress-nginx
        namespace: flux-system
  values:
    controller:
      replicaCount: 3
      resources:
        requests:
          cpu: 100m
          memory: 256Mi
  upgrade:
    remediation:
      retries: 3
  rollback:
    timeout: 5m

# HelmRepository source
apiVersion: source.toolkit.fluxcd.io/v1beta2
kind: HelmRepository
metadata:
  name: ingress-nginx
  namespace: flux-system
spec:
  interval: 1h
  url: https://kubernetes.github.io/ingress-nginx</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">ArgoCD — Install and Application Example</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4"># Install ArgoCD
kubectl create namespace argocd
kubectl apply -n argocd -f \
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/argoproj/argo-cd/stable/manifests/install.yaml

# Access UI (port-forward)
kubectl port-forward svc/argocd-server -n argocd 8080:443

# ArgoCD Application manifest
apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: nginx-ingress
  namespace: argocd
  finalizers:
    - resources-finalizer.argocd.argoproj.io
spec:
  project: infrastructure
  source:
    repoURL: https://kubernetes.github.io/ingress-nginx
    chart: ingress-nginx
    targetRevision: 4.9.0
    helm:
      values: |
        controller:
          replicaCount: 3
          resources:
            requests:
              cpu: 100m
              memory: 256Mi
  destination:
    server: https://kubernetes.default.svc
    namespace: ingress-nginx
  syncPolicy:
    automated:
      prune: true
      selfHeal: true
    syncOptions:
      - CreateNamespace=true
    retry:
      limit: 5
      backoff:
        duration: 5s
        maxDuration: 3m
        factor: 2</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Flux SOPS Secrets Integration</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4"># Generate age key pair
age-keygen -o age.agekey

# Add private key to Flux as a secret
kubectl create secret generic sops-age \
  --namespace=flux-system \
  --from-file=age.agekey=./age.agekey

# Encrypt a secret with SOPS
sops --age=$(cat age.agekey | grep "public key" | sed 's/.*: //') \
  --encrypt --in-place mysecret.yaml

# .sops.yaml — auto-encrypt any file matching the pattern
creation_rules:
  - path_regex: .*/secrets/.*\.yaml
    age: age1xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx

# Flux Kustomization with SOPS decryption
apiVersion: kustomize.toolkit.fluxcd.io/v1
kind: Kustomization
metadata:
  name: apps
  namespace: flux-system
spec:
  interval: 10m
  path: ./clusters/production/apps
  prune: true
  sourceRef:
    kind: GitRepository
    name: fleet-infra
  decryption:
    provider: sops
    secretRef:
      name: sops-age</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Decision Guide</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-text-muted space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong>Choose ArgoCD</strong> when: teams need self-service deployments via UI, strong RBAC needed for multiple teams, one-click rollback is important, Argo Rollouts for canary/blue-green, or you want a polished UI experience.</li>
    <li><strong>Choose Flux</strong> when: pure GitOps without UI dependencies preferred, SOPS secrets integration needed, Kubernetes-native resource model, smaller ops overhead (no UI to maintain), or multi-cluster fleet management with Flux's sharding model.</li>
    <li><strong>Both are CNCF graduated</strong> — there's no wrong choice. Many large organizations use ArgoCD for developer-facing app deployments and Flux for platform bootstrapping.</li>
  </ul>

  <AdUnit slot="auto" format="auto" label="Advertisement" />
  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
  <ToolPageCta currentTool="gitops-flux-vs-argocd" relatedTags={["kubernetes", "gitops", "flux", "argocd", "devops", "ci-cd", "helm"]} />
</BaseLayout>
